## 3. Dashboard Route Tree — Structural Mismatch with Components

### Route tree:
```
app/dashboard/
├── layout.tsx          ← The "god layout" — authentication, sockets, sidebars, chat widgets
├── page.tsx            ← Role router
├── admin/              ← 21 sub-routes
├── agent/
│   └── marketing/
│       ├── layout.tsx  ← Mobile FAB
│       ├── page.tsx    ← Agent overview (duplicate of management/page.tsx)
│       └── management/ ← The "portal" (own sidebar, own layout)
│           ├── layout.tsx
│           ├── page.tsx
│           ├── clients/
│           ├── notes/
│           ├── tasks/
│           └── calendar/
├── client/             ← 12 sub-routes
└── guest/
```

### The Portal-within-Dashboard Problem

The **management portal** (`/dashboard/agent/marketing/management/`) is a completely separate shell (its own sidebar `ManagementSidebar`, its own scroll container, its own error boundary) nested *inside* the global `DashboardLayout`. This is handled by path-string detection in the layout:

```typescript
// dashboard/layout.tsx line 91-93
const isInPortal = 
  !!pathname &&
  (pathname === PORTAL_ROOT || pathname.startsWith(PORTAL_ROOT + '/'));
```

And then the global sidebar is conditionally suppressed:
```typescript
{!isInPortal && <Sidebar />}
```

And then the `ml-60` margin offset is switched between two different localStorage keys:
```typescript
isInPortal
  ? (portalSidebarCollapsed ? 'md:ml-16' : 'md:ml-60')
  : (sidebarCollapsed ? 'md:ml-16' : 'md:ml-60')
```

> [!CAUTION]
> This is brittle. Any route path change to the management portal breaks the portal detection. The right architecture is to move the management portal **outside** of `/dashboard/` entirely (e.g. `/portal/marketing/`) or to use a [Route Group](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/routing/route-groups) `(portal)` at the route level to opt-out of the global dashboard layout without string matching.

